{"title":"MacroHFT: Memory Augmented Context-aware Reinforcement Learning On High Frequency Trading","domain":"RL","seeds":[{"problem":"Single RL agents struggle in non-stationary, highly volatile crypto markets; prior hierarchical methods typically rely on trend alone and select a single agent per step, ignoring volatility and leading to biased decisions.","method":"Decompose sequential market data into fixed-length chunks and label each chunk by two macro indicators—trend (slope from a low-pass-filtered linear fit) and volatility (average volatility)—then partition by quantiles to form six regimes (bull/flat/bear and high/medium/low volatility). Train a separate DDQN-based sub-agent on each labeled subset and select models by validation performance on the corresponding regime, yielding a pool of six specialized policies. This market decomposition enhances specialization and mitigates overfitting by exposing each agent to more homogeneous dynamics and explicit context during training."},{"problem":"HFT policies tend to overfit a few features and fail to adapt to recent context and the trader’s current position, hurting responsiveness and risk control at minute granularity.","method":"Equip each sub-agent with a conditional adapter: embed recent context features and current position into a condition vector, then use adaptive LayerNorm (scale-and-shift from the condition) to modulate the single-state embedding before the dueling DDQN head. Optimize with TD error plus a KL term to dynamic-programming-derived optimal Q-values (Optimal Value Supervisor), stabilizing learning and anchoring action-values. This conditioning lets policies adjust to market context and holdings in real time, improving robustness and adaptability."},{"problem":"At the meta level, rewards for similar states can vary sharply and rare market shocks are hard to capture with standard replay, while selecting a single sub-agent yields one-sided behavior.","method":"Train a hyper-agent that produces softmax weights over all sub-agents and forms a mixed action-value Q_hyper = Σ_i w_i Q_sub_i, with its own conditional adapter driven by slope and volatility indicators. Augment training with an episodic memory that stores recent hidden states, actions, and one-step Q targets; at each step, retrieve the top-m similar experiences (via L2-distance/kernel weighting) to compute an auxiliary value target added to the loss alongside TD and KL-to-demonstration terms. This memory-augmented mixture stabilizes Q estimates across similar contexts and enables rapid adaptation to transient, extreme market movements."}]}
